{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Rose Robertson","author":"Rose Robertson"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"2fe97b56-421f-5640-961b-feca3e4dfa7b","excerpt":"To me, 2018 (the year I was/am off on maternity leave) was the year that VS Code  really  blew up in popularity. So although I had switchedâ€¦","html":"<p>To me, 2018 (the year I was/am off on maternity leave) was the year that VS Code <em>really</em> blew up in popularity.</p>\n<p>So although I had switched to Atom from Sublime a year or two earlier, I decided to switch AGAINâ€¦ because no one is nearly as obsessed with Atom like they are for VS Code and since now Microsoft owned both editors, I might as well switch to the preferred child.</p>\n<p>AND since Iâ€™m not working at the moment and have a bit of time during baby naps to just nerd out, I got to spend a lot of time researching and getting my setup <em>juust</em> right.</p>\n<h3>First up: The icon</h3>\n<p>Iâ€™m not usually one to replace app icons to be honest, it just seems a bitâ€¦ extreme? Like it feels more pure to stick with how the vendor intended it to be. BUT. I just really didnâ€™t like the existing icon and I decided to break my usual rule ðŸ˜„</p>\n<p>I decided to go with <a href=\"https://dribbble.com/shots/3169976-Visual-Studio-Code-Icon-Revamp\">this icon by Lex Tang</a>. It looks pretty good:</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/4227f/vscode-icon.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 22.568807339449542%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"vscode icon\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/fb8a0/vscode-icon.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/1a291/vscode-icon.png 148w,\n/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/2bc4a/vscode-icon.png 295w,\n/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/fb8a0/vscode-icon.png 590w,\n/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/526de/vscode-icon.png 885w,\n/static/0b8d394af65316e93a2858c8f4150989/4227f/vscode-icon.png 1090w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>\n<h3>OK what about theme?</h3>\n<p>Iâ€™ve long been a fan of <a href=\"https://github.com/chriskempson/tomorrow-theme\">Tomorrow Night Eighties</a> in all my editors, but I decided to take a break and try something new. <a href=\"https://dev.to/aspittel/my-visual-studio-code-setup-1emn\">Ali Spittel</a> mentioned <a href=\"https://draculatheme.com\">Dracula Dark</a> andâ€¦ Yep, love it.</p>\n<p>\n  <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/df48b/dracula.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n  \n  <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n    style=\"position: relative; display: block;  max-width: 590px; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;\"\n  >\n    <span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n      style=\"padding-bottom: 34.0782122905028%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n    >\n      <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        style=\"width: 100%; height: 100%; margin: 0; vertical-align: middle; position: absolute; top: 0; left: 0; box-shadow: inset 0px 0px 0px 400px white;\"\n        alt=\"dracula\"\n        title=\"\"\n        src=\"/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/fb8a0/dracula.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/1a291/dracula.png 148w,\n/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/2bc4a/dracula.png 295w,\n/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/fb8a0/dracula.png 590w,\n/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/526de/dracula.png 885w,\n/static/b46024a1c8236156d54f84fa9771611e/df48b/dracula.png 1074w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n      />\n    </span>\n  </span>\n  \n  </a>\n    </p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Setting Up Visual Studio Code","date":"November 03, 2018"}}},"pageContext":{"slug":"/setting-up-vscode/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/maternity-leave-experimentation/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Maternity Leave Experimentation"}},"next":null}}